{"questionId":"7637","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{}_{15}^{32}{\\text{P}}\">\n  <msubsup>\n    <mrow>\n\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>15</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>32</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </msubsup>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>P</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> is formed when a nucleus of deuterium (<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{}_{1}^{2}{\\text{H}}\">\n  <msubsup>\n    <mrow>\n\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </msubsup>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>H</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>) collides with a nucleus of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{}_{15}^{31}{\\text{P}}\">\n  <msubsup>\n    <mrow>\n\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>15</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>31</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </msubsup>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>P</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>. The radius of a deuterium nucleus is 1.5 fm.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{}_{15}^{32}{\\text{P}}\">\n  <msubsup>\n    <mrow>\n\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>15</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>32</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </msubsup>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>P</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;undergoes beta-minus (β<sup>–</sup>) decay. Explain why the energy gained by the emitted&nbsp;beta particles in this decay is not the same for every beta particle.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>«electron» <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">antineutrino</span> also emitted ✔</p>\n<p>energy split between electron and «anti»neutrino ✔</p>","meta":{"questionId":"7637","referenceCode":"18N.2.HL.TZ0.6c","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"15 32 P undergoes beta-minus (β–) decay. Explain why th